1
00:02:54,560 --> 00:02:57,438
<i>Stay with us for
blood-chilling suspense...</i>

2
00:02:57,600 --> 00:03:00,398
<i>...blackmail, murder,
intrigue and love.</i>

3
00:03:00,560 --> 00:03:02,516
<i>Next on Channel 8.</i>

4
00:03:02,680 --> 00:03:05,148
<i>-a tourist, visiting a friend,
was struck...</i>

5
00:03:05,320 --> 00:03:08,630
<i>...by a 30-pound block as he
walk ed down the stage-door alley.</i>

6
00:03:08,800 --> 00:03:11,394
<i>The cinder block hit me
on the flat side...</i>

7
00:03:11,560 --> 00:03:14,074
<i>...of the block itself,
as if it were hurled at me.</i>

8
00:03:14,240 --> 00:03:16,435
<i>-when the ferry dock ed,
he was napping.</i>

9
00:03:16,600 --> 00:03:20,752
<i>A deck hand wok e him and told him
to drive off. But Max was in reverse.</i>

10
00:03:20,920 --> 00:03:23,992
<i>He went right off the back of the ferry.
He drowned.</i>

11
00:03:24,160 --> 00:03:27,357
<i>But if you were complaining
about the weather this week end...</i>

12
00:03:27,520 --> 00:03:29,954
<i>...it could have been worse.
A series of floods...</i>

13
00:03:30,120 --> 00:03:32,588
-I guess it's that time.
-You want any help?

14
00:03:34,240 --> 00:03:37,516
There was a terrific recipe for capon
in the Times today.

15
00:03:38,880 --> 00:03:40,996
Takes two minutes.

16
00:03:41,280 --> 00:03:43,271
<i>The National Guard has been
called out...</i>

17
00:03:43,440 --> 00:03:45,351
<i>...and some people may have to-</i>

18
00:04:10,760 --> 00:04:15,117
Enid, someone's moving into
the Warren place.

19
00:04:15,280 --> 00:04:16,793
So?

20
00:04:17,880 --> 00:04:20,235
It's a funny time to be moving.

21
00:04:21,800 --> 00:04:24,075
I don't see any kids' stuff.

22
00:04:24,520 --> 00:04:25,839
Thank God.

23
00:04:32,120 --> 00:04:34,998
Maybe we should ask them over
for a drink tonight.

24
00:04:35,200 --> 00:04:38,317
-It being their first night and all.
-Tomorrow will be fine.

25
00:04:38,480 --> 00:04:40,675
Well, tomorrow's not tonight,
you know.

26
00:04:40,840 --> 00:04:43,877
-And it would be nice.
-There's plenty of time to be nice.

27
00:04:44,040 --> 00:04:46,031
You don't have to push it.

28
00:05:20,640 --> 00:05:22,949
I think they've got a dog.

29
00:05:23,200 --> 00:05:26,476
Kalinqashe, the dog spirit,
is swift and faithful.

30
00:05:26,640 --> 00:05:30,838
I don't care. I don't want him
in my garden digging up my bulbs.

31
00:05:31,320 --> 00:05:34,118
Who would want your bulbs?

32
00:06:32,840 --> 00:06:34,751
Hello.

33
00:06:35,760 --> 00:06:39,196
-What can I do for you?
-Anything you like.

34
00:06:39,360 --> 00:06:42,272
The question is,
what do you want in return?

35
00:06:48,200 --> 00:06:51,715
Hi. I'm Ramona.
I just moved in next door.

36
00:06:51,880 --> 00:06:54,838
-Oh, really?
-Really.

37
00:07:00,040 --> 00:07:01,871
Who's this?

38
00:07:02,440 --> 00:07:05,113
-Your girlfriend?
-No, that's my daughter, Elaine.

39
00:07:06,400 --> 00:07:08,550
That's a hot one.

40
00:07:22,720 --> 00:07:25,029
By the way, my name is Earl Keese.

41
00:07:27,400 --> 00:07:29,914
I was real friendly
with a boy named Earl once.

42
00:07:30,680 --> 00:07:32,989
Well, twice really.

43
00:07:34,320 --> 00:07:36,880
So you're all moved in next door, huh?

44
00:07:37,040 --> 00:07:40,191
It's a very good house. I imagine
you'll want to freshen it up.

45
00:07:40,360 --> 00:07:42,351
Give it a new coat of paint,
mow the lawn.

46
00:07:42,520 --> 00:07:43,999
Is your wife here?

47
00:07:44,280 --> 00:07:45,793
She's in the kitchen.

48
00:07:46,000 --> 00:07:49,913
-She's dying to meet you. I'll get her.
-No, no, I don't want to meet her.

49
00:07:50,080 --> 00:07:52,514
I hope we're gonna be friends.

50
00:07:53,200 --> 00:07:56,431
We were very friendly
with the Warrens next door.

51
00:07:56,720 --> 00:07:58,711
But we weren't that close.

52
00:07:58,920 --> 00:08:01,036
I mean, we were next-door close.

53
00:08:01,240 --> 00:08:06,155
I didn't mean that kind of close.
I mean "close" close.

54
00:08:06,800 --> 00:08:08,472
Is your wife making dinner?

55
00:08:09,440 --> 00:08:11,590
She's fixing a great capon.

56
00:08:11,760 --> 00:08:14,149
It was in the Times today.

57
00:08:15,640 --> 00:08:17,631
Would you Like to stay for dinner?

58
00:08:17,880 --> 00:08:20,155
Are there more of you?

59
00:08:20,360 --> 00:08:22,590
Is there a Mr. Ramona?

60
00:08:22,760 --> 00:08:25,274
You go ask your wife if it's okay.

61
00:08:25,480 --> 00:08:28,074
No, it's no problem, really.

62
00:08:28,240 --> 00:08:29,798
Don't argue with me, Earl.

63
00:08:30,280 --> 00:08:32,953
You wouldn’t want me
to have to pull down your pants...

64
00:08:33,120 --> 00:08:34,633
...and spank your little buns...

65
00:08:34,840 --> 00:08:36,353
...would you?

66
00:08:48,160 --> 00:08:50,674
Don't you go away. I'll be right back.

67
00:08:51,480 --> 00:08:52,913
Okay?

68
00:09:03,320 --> 00:09:07,154
-How many frozen waffles you want?
-Waffles? What happened to the capon?

69
00:09:07,320 --> 00:09:09,151
-What capon?
-You said you read...

70
00:09:09,320 --> 00:09:12,676
-... an incredible recipe for it.
-I didn't say we were having it.

71
00:09:12,880 --> 00:09:15,235
Leave it to you
to take something for granted.

72
00:09:15,400 --> 00:09:17,277
Frozen waffles is all we've got.

73
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:20,150
Weren't you gonna pick up steaks
for tomorrow?

74
00:09:20,320 --> 00:09:21,878
You're asking for steak?

75
00:09:22,040 --> 00:09:24,349
You could have picked up
some cheap ones.

76
00:09:24,520 --> 00:09:26,750
I will not eat cheap meat.

77
00:09:34,360 --> 00:09:35,873
<i>No! No!</i>

78
00:09:46,520 --> 00:09:49,080
-May I help you?
-Hi, Earl. I'm Vic.

79
00:09:49,280 --> 00:09:51,999
I'm sure Ramona's already told you
my whole life story.

80
00:09:52,160 --> 00:09:56,153
<i>-No, but you must be her...
-That's me, Like it or not.</i>

81
00:09:56,320 --> 00:09:59,790
If you know what I mean. Have a seat.

82
00:10:01,760 --> 00:10:04,718
So, what do you say, neighbor?

83
00:10:06,040 --> 00:10:08,429
Welcome to the end of the road,
I guess.

84
00:10:08,720 --> 00:10:10,153
-It's a great house.
-Thank you.

85
00:10:10,320 --> 00:10:13,995
I mean mine. More rooms than we
need, really, but I couldn’t resist.

86
00:10:14,160 --> 00:10:15,229
It was a steal.

87
00:10:15,400 --> 00:10:17,391
What's on the menu, pal?
I'm starved.

88
00:10:18,440 --> 00:10:22,115
We haven't eaten all day. We could eat
a baby's butt through a park bench.

89
00:10:22,280 --> 00:10:25,352
I'm afraid I spoke too soon earlier.

90
00:10:25,520 --> 00:10:28,398
We haven't got enough.
Enid didn't get to her shopping today.

91
00:10:28,560 --> 00:10:31,154
Well, no sweat.
I'll just go and get some takeout.

92
00:10:31,320 --> 00:10:34,357
There's nothing around here
except the standard burgers...

93
00:10:34,520 --> 00:10:37,398
-... greasy dogs and a gummy pizza.
-I can do better than that.

94
00:10:37,560 --> 00:10:40,074
You just leave everything
to Captain Vic.

95
00:10:40,800 --> 00:10:45,237
Look, friend, if I do the running,
I know you’ll wanna spring for the tab.

96
00:10:46,080 --> 00:10:47,399
Okay.

97
00:10:55,960 --> 00:10:57,916
Thirty bucks?
For four grown people?

98
00:10:58,080 --> 00:11:01,834
Where have you been? It takes
30 bucks just to look at a menu.

99
00:11:04,520 --> 00:11:07,159
-This is a $2 bill.
-Let me see that.

100
00:11:07,320 --> 00:11:09,436
Gee, I thought it was a 20.

101
00:11:09,920 --> 00:11:13,071
-Really.
-Well, people palm them off that way.

102
00:11:13,240 --> 00:11:16,437
You never know who's gonna
stick it to you, do you, Earl?

103
00:11:16,600 --> 00:11:20,513
Look, if 32 bucks isn't enough,
we can always do it some other night.

104
00:11:20,680 --> 00:11:23,513
Why don't we do it now.
Let's have your car keys, okay?

105
00:11:23,680 --> 00:11:26,399
-My car keys?
-Yeah, my brakes are shot.

106
00:11:26,560 --> 00:11:29,950
Why don't I get the food? I'm the one
who's supposed to be neighborly.

107
00:11:30,120 --> 00:11:32,714
You stay here and my wife
will keep you company.

108
00:11:32,920 --> 00:11:37,152
Forget it. If you insist on paying for
dinner, the least I can do is go get it.

109
00:11:37,520 --> 00:11:39,909
What I don't understand
is where you're going.

110
00:11:40,080 --> 00:11:41,877
There's no place decent around here.

111
00:11:42,040 --> 00:11:45,430
If you must know, it's a new place,
opened up on the other side of town.

112
00:11:45,600 --> 00:11:48,398
Near the train station.
Across from the warehouse.

113
00:11:48,560 --> 00:11:50,118
Italian.

114
00:11:50,320 --> 00:11:53,312
I commute, I go by there twice a day,
five days a week...

115
00:11:53,480 --> 00:11:55,835
...and I've never seen
a restaurant around there.

116
00:11:57,240 --> 00:11:59,037
You calling me a liar?

117
00:11:59,200 --> 00:12:00,792
<i>No, I...</i>

118
00:12:01,200 --> 00:12:03,668
I'm just not very observant,
I guess.

119
00:12:03,840 --> 00:12:06,752
I can't blame you.
They don't have their sign up yet.

120
00:12:06,920 --> 00:12:10,595
But it's got a cute name:
Caesar's Garlic Wars.

121
00:12:12,240 --> 00:12:14,754
Okay. Why don't you
get some ravioli...

122
00:12:14,920 --> 00:12:17,559
...and some- What do you
call those stuffed clams?

123
00:12:17,720 --> 00:12:22,316
-Stuffed clams.
-Yeah. And some scampi and garlic.

124
00:12:22,480 --> 00:12:25,392
Whatever I get, Earl,
I first have to get going.

125
00:12:25,560 --> 00:12:27,357
I'll get the keys.

126
00:12:28,240 --> 00:12:30,800
Why don't you stay here
and make yourself at home.

127
00:12:30,960 --> 00:12:32,916
I'll be right here.

128
00:12:47,520 --> 00:12:49,238
Hi.

129
00:12:50,560 --> 00:12:53,677
Took a bath. There's a dead rat
in our tub over there.

130
00:12:54,040 --> 00:12:56,156
Vic said not to move it.

131
00:12:56,840 --> 00:13:00,355
Took a pill. Moving always makes me
kind of hyper.

132
00:13:00,960 --> 00:13:02,871
I hope you don't mind.

133
00:13:03,480 --> 00:13:05,516
Yeah. Sure. I don't mind.

134
00:13:05,680 --> 00:13:07,910
Oh, you do mind, don't you?

135
00:13:10,240 --> 00:13:12,435
Vic's going out for Italian food.

136
00:13:12,600 --> 00:13:16,434
You come down and join us
whenever you can, okay?

137
00:13:17,600 --> 00:13:19,795
What are you so nervous about, Earl?

138
00:13:21,120 --> 00:13:23,680
<i>Afraid Vic will think you're up here...</i>

139
00:13:23,880 --> 00:13:25,791
...chewing me?

140
00:13:44,880 --> 00:13:46,393
What are you doing? Robbing me?

141
00:13:46,560 --> 00:13:49,279
Looking for a pencil to write down
what you want for supper.

142
00:13:49,440 --> 00:13:50,839
You got a pencil in your hand.

143
00:13:51,000 --> 00:13:53,958
$327. Is that all you had
at the end of last month?

144
00:13:54,120 --> 00:13:56,714
That's none of your business.
Stay out of there, please.

145
00:13:56,880 --> 00:14:00,839
-I just wanted to get the order right.
-Why don't we go downstairs.

146
00:14:01,040 --> 00:14:02,359
Sure.

147
00:14:02,600 --> 00:14:04,272
After you.

148
00:14:05,000 --> 00:14:07,355
-So, what do you want?
-Make it simple.

149
00:14:07,520 --> 00:14:11,115
Spaghetti, meatballs, a salad.
Whatever you want for you and-

150
00:14:11,280 --> 00:14:13,669
What's not simple
is how I get to the restaurant.

151
00:14:13,840 --> 00:14:16,400
-Use my car.
-Has it got a key or a rubber band...

152
00:14:16,560 --> 00:14:18,835
-... you wind up?
-Why don't I go with you.

153
00:14:19,000 --> 00:14:22,117
Afraid I'll steal your car?
That's why I moved in next door?

154
00:14:22,280 --> 00:14:25,078
So I could rip off your car
and move somewhere else?

155
00:14:25,280 --> 00:14:27,919
-There you go.
-Back in a flash, pal.

156
00:14:58,520 --> 00:15:01,910
Waffles are browning.
Always a thrilling sight.

157
00:15:02,080 --> 00:15:03,911
Good news, Enid.

158
00:15:04,200 --> 00:15:06,634
Italian food is on the way.

159
00:15:07,360 --> 00:15:08,679
You arranged it?

160
00:15:08,840 --> 00:15:11,593
Well, more or less.
I invited the neighbors.

161
00:15:11,760 --> 00:15:13,557
Oh, you met them.

162
00:15:14,120 --> 00:15:15,599
What did you think?

163
00:15:32,080 --> 00:15:33,149
Earl?

164
00:15:33,320 --> 00:15:34,799
They're...

165
00:15:35,680 --> 00:15:37,352
...different.

166
00:15:38,960 --> 00:15:41,076
I guess I'll go up and get dressed.

167
00:15:42,640 --> 00:15:43,959
Upstairs?

168
00:15:44,120 --> 00:15:45,633
What for?

169
00:15:46,480 --> 00:15:47,913
You said they were coming over.

170
00:15:48,080 --> 00:15:50,548
Well, they're not dressing.
They're barely dressed.

171
00:15:50,720 --> 00:15:54,952
I mean, you could go
in the kitchen and set the table.

172
00:15:55,120 --> 00:15:58,476
And turn the waffles off.
I'll be there in a minute to help you.

173
00:15:58,640 --> 00:16:01,279
You got lots to do down here.

174
00:16:03,440 --> 00:16:06,034
Yeah, there is something I forgot to do.

175
00:17:05,360 --> 00:17:08,033
That's a boy.
You want some steak?

176
00:21:05,800 --> 00:21:08,439
Don't tell me, you must be
our new neighbor. Come on in.

177
00:21:08,600 --> 00:21:10,556
Thanks a lot.

178
00:21:20,000 --> 00:21:21,991
Someone's stolen our truck...

179
00:21:22,160 --> 00:21:24,469
...and I need to use the phone
to call the police.

180
00:21:24,640 --> 00:21:27,757
Use the phone in the kitchen.
What a terrible thing, your first day.

181
00:21:27,920 --> 00:21:30,559
It's even worse than just that.
Baby was in the back.

182
00:21:30,720 --> 00:21:33,598
-Oh, my.
-Oh! Oh! Oh!

183
00:21:34,160 --> 00:21:35,718
Vic. Your baby's drowning!

184
00:21:35,880 --> 00:21:38,348
No chance.
Why should my dog be drowning?

185
00:21:39,200 --> 00:21:40,519
Dog?

186
00:21:41,640 --> 00:21:42,914
I thought "child. "

187
00:21:43,080 --> 00:21:45,913
We haven't any children.
Unless Ramona just pumped one out...

188
00:21:46,080 --> 00:21:48,913
...and didn't tell me.
She calls the dog " Baby. "

189
00:21:49,080 --> 00:21:51,514
-She calls the dog " Baby"?
-Yeah. He's fine.

190
00:21:51,680 --> 00:21:54,194
I just saw him around the back there.
When I drove up.

191
00:21:54,360 --> 00:21:56,555
He's digging up something
in your flowerbed.

192
00:21:56,720 --> 00:21:57,994
My flowerbed?

193
00:22:03,000 --> 00:22:04,399
Hi, Enid.

194
00:22:06,600 --> 00:22:08,477
Hi, Vic.

195
00:22:08,840 --> 00:22:10,193
Oh, we met hours ago.

196
00:22:10,360 --> 00:22:12,794
Earl here was worried about Baby.

197
00:22:12,960 --> 00:22:15,679
Oh, he's no trouble at all.
He's a perfect gentleman.

198
00:22:15,840 --> 00:22:19,628
-Leave him with me any time you want.
-Don't worry, I will.

199
00:22:19,920 --> 00:22:21,194
They spoil him awfully.

200
00:22:21,360 --> 00:22:25,239
I want him to have every advantage
I was denied as a young dog.

201
00:22:25,400 --> 00:22:27,868
Well, here are your keys, Mr. Keese.

202
00:22:28,200 --> 00:22:31,875
Let's dig into this stuff
before the sauce turns into penicillin.

203
00:22:32,680 --> 00:22:35,069
Why don't you Look for Ramona.

204
00:22:35,720 --> 00:22:38,792
-Me?
-Finders keepers, Earl. After all...

205
00:22:38,960 --> 00:22:41,520
...I know what goes on out here
in the suburbs.

206
00:22:42,000 --> 00:22:44,036
That's why we moved here.

207
00:22:46,840 --> 00:22:48,353
Oh, Vic.

208
00:22:51,680 --> 00:22:55,958
-What do you think, Earl?
-Don't do that. You are outrageous.

209
00:23:09,200 --> 00:23:11,589
Too bad about Vic's truck, Earl.

210
00:23:13,680 --> 00:23:16,035
Well, I was just pushing it
into my garage...

211
00:23:16,200 --> 00:23:18,794
...to hide it from him, you know,
kind of a joke.

212
00:23:18,960 --> 00:23:21,758
-It was an accident.
-It could happen to anybody.

213
00:23:22,040 --> 00:23:23,951
I think 1500 should take care of it.

214
00:23:24,120 --> 00:23:26,588
Fifteen hundred? Dollars?

215
00:23:26,800 --> 00:23:30,839
It was just a joke. I mean, I'm sure
your insurance will cover most of it...

216
00:23:31,000 --> 00:23:33,958
...and I'll pay the deductible.
What is it, 100 or so?

217
00:23:34,120 --> 00:23:38,636
For the truck.
Keeping me quiet is a little extra.

218
00:23:40,680 --> 00:23:42,432
I don't believe it.

219
00:23:42,720 --> 00:23:44,039
You're blackmailing me.

220
00:23:44,200 --> 00:23:46,634
Hey, what are neighbors for?

221
00:23:47,000 --> 00:23:49,116
Oh, make it cash.

222
00:24:01,960 --> 00:24:04,997
Hey, come on in, buddy.
Help yourself.

223
00:24:24,440 --> 00:24:26,954
Well, here we all are.

224
00:24:27,360 --> 00:24:28,634
To Vic and Ramona.

225
00:24:28,800 --> 00:24:31,394
For bringing a breath of fresh air
to our neighborhood.

226
00:24:31,560 --> 00:24:35,075
May we have many, many years
of your lovely company.

227
00:24:40,080 --> 00:24:41,832
Do they have any country fairs here?

228
00:24:42,000 --> 00:24:45,913
Where they do things Like see
which bull has the biggest balls?

229
00:24:50,240 --> 00:24:54,791
This isn't really country. It's more
a suburban bedroom community.

230
00:24:54,960 --> 00:24:57,952
The locals are in service trades.
They're not farmers.

231
00:24:58,160 --> 00:24:59,991
Maybe we can measure their balls.

232
00:25:03,120 --> 00:25:06,078
Or we could start with yours,
if you Like.

233
00:25:14,200 --> 00:25:15,428
Good, is it?

234
00:25:16,360 --> 00:25:18,954
-Delicious.
-I must call Caesar's...

235
00:25:19,120 --> 00:25:20,678
...and compliment the chef.

236
00:25:20,960 --> 00:25:23,474
Tell me, were they crowded
this evening?

237
00:25:23,680 --> 00:25:25,193
-What?
-Caesar's.

238
00:25:25,360 --> 00:25:27,669
Friday night, the only place in town.

239
