01:03:47,880 --> 01:03:50,189
The rear axle’s broken.

714
01:03:50,480 --> 01:03:52,755
Well, I'll get it fixed. It's only fair.

715
01:03:52,920 --> 01:03:57,471
-Forget it. Give it a decent burial.
-You don't want your truck?

716
01:03:57,640 --> 01:03:59,358
You don't get it, do you?

717
01:04:01,440 --> 01:04:04,193
I'm moving. Away.

718
01:04:08,320 --> 01:04:11,949
Moving? What do you mean, moving?
You haven't been here 24 hours yet.

719
01:04:12,120 --> 01:04:13,951
-What's wrong?
-I don't know. That swamp.

720
01:04:14,120 --> 01:04:16,588
In the summer, it must be
a swing club for mosquitoes.

721
01:04:16,760 --> 01:04:18,432
The county sprays.
It's no problem.

722
01:04:18,600 --> 01:04:20,909
Those lines,
they're too close to the house.

723
01:04:21,080 --> 01:04:23,275
They cause hair loss,
Lumbar ecstimiosis...

724
01:04:23,440 --> 01:04:25,237
...post cortical lesions and impotency.

725
01:04:25,400 --> 01:04:26,674
It's just a myth.

726
01:04:26,840 --> 01:04:30,071
The power company wouldn’t
put them up if they were dangerous.

727
01:04:32,600 --> 01:04:35,114
Of course, it's your right to move,
I guess.

728
01:04:35,280 --> 01:04:38,317
But as far as I'm concerned,
I'd honestly Like you to stay.

729
01:04:38,480 --> 01:04:39,913
You would?

730
01:04:40,120 --> 01:04:43,271
Well, to tell you the truth...

731
01:04:43,480 --> 01:04:45,869
...I haven't got
any friends around here.

732
01:04:46,960 --> 01:04:50,953
I mean it.
As crazy as Last night was...

733
01:04:51,160 --> 01:04:53,958
<i>...even though I hated your guts
through most of it...</i>

734
01:04:54,120 --> 01:04:55,599
...I really had...

735
01:04:55,760 --> 01:04:57,239
...a good time.

736
01:04:58,760 --> 01:05:00,113
Good time.

737
01:05:00,360 --> 01:05:05,070
I can't remember a better time
on any Friday night I've ever had.

738
01:05:05,280 --> 01:05:06,633
Neither can I.

739
01:05:06,800 --> 01:05:08,711
I bet Ramona doesn't wanna move,
does she?

740
01:05:08,880 --> 01:05:11,633
She's not moving.
You can have her. She's all paid for.

741
01:05:12,680 --> 01:05:15,877
This is another joke.
Of course you're gonna take your wife.

742
01:05:16,040 --> 01:05:17,712
She might come in handy.

743
01:05:17,880 --> 01:05:21,395
-Who says she's my wife?
-She's not your wife?

744
01:05:21,560 --> 01:05:23,710
-Whose wife is she?
-I couldn’t care less.

745
01:05:23,880 --> 01:05:26,440
If you want her, she's yours.
With my compliments.

746
01:05:26,600 --> 01:05:29,194
Well, I gotta pack.
It's been nice knowing you.

747
01:05:32,600 --> 01:05:34,192
Enid. Open this door.

748
01:05:34,400 --> 01:05:36,038
It's open.

749
01:05:40,080 --> 01:05:41,559
Where's Enid?

750
01:05:42,960 --> 01:05:46,430
What the hell's going on in here?
Why was that door Locked before?

751
01:05:46,600 --> 01:05:47,953
Where's my wife?

752
01:05:48,160 --> 01:05:49,559
She's your wife.

753
01:05:49,760 --> 01:05:52,433
Oh, yeah? Well, you know
what Vic just told me?

754
01:05:52,600 --> 01:05:54,033
-What?
-He's moving.

755
01:05:54,200 --> 01:05:56,077
Moving away.
And leaving you here.

756
01:05:56,240 --> 01:05:58,993
He said I could have you.
What do you think about that?

757
01:05:59,280 --> 01:06:02,113
-Sounds exciting.
-I'm serious.

758
01:06:02,320 --> 01:06:04,436
So am I.

759
01:06:06,880 --> 01:06:08,871
For God's sake,
Ramona, cover yourself.

760
01:06:09,040 --> 01:06:10,553
Come on.

761
01:06:10,960 --> 01:06:14,396
-People just don't do this kind of thing.
-But we could.

762
01:06:16,240 --> 01:06:17,992
Don't worry about Enid.

763
01:06:18,160 --> 01:06:22,358
She's not around.
We won't be disturbed.

764
01:06:24,000 --> 01:06:26,514
Come on, before it gets cold.

765
01:06:26,680 --> 01:06:27,954
I can't.

766
01:06:28,120 --> 01:06:30,270
I know. You're worried about Vic.

767
01:06:30,760 --> 01:06:32,955
No, I'm not worried about Vic.

768
01:06:33,120 --> 01:06:35,236
-He's next door packing.
-All right, baby.

769
01:06:35,440 --> 01:06:38,079
-Baby, watch it. All right, sweetheart.
-Oh, boy.

770
01:06:38,720 --> 01:06:42,110
One time.
All right. All right, sweetie.

771
01:06:43,320 --> 01:06:46,676
Pull out, babe, pull out. All right.

772
01:06:46,880 --> 01:06:50,077
All right. Looking good.

773
01:06:51,520 --> 01:06:55,718
Pull out, babe, pull out. All right.

774
01:06:55,920 --> 01:06:57,717
Jesus, what a case.

775
01:06:57,880 --> 01:06:59,950
Two minutes ago, he said
he was moving away.

776
01:07:00,120 --> 01:07:01,633
I think Vic was right about you.

777
01:07:02,240 --> 01:07:03,514
About what?

778
01:07:04,800 --> 01:07:08,270
He said up is definitely not
your direction.

779
01:07:09,480 --> 01:07:11,789
-Is that what he said?
-Yeah.

780
01:07:11,960 --> 01:07:14,520
Okay, we'll just see about that.

781
01:07:14,720 --> 01:07:17,314
That's my Little sweetheart. All right.

782
01:07:18,400 --> 01:07:24,236
All right, dive, baby, dive.
Let's see a screaming dive. All right.

783
01:07:24,400 --> 01:07:26,960
-Hi, neighbor.
-Hi.

784
01:07:27,120 --> 01:07:31,875
Now, I'm just gonna go under
the covers and take a Little inventory.

785
01:07:32,040 --> 01:07:36,830
-Promise you won't go away.
-I promise.

786
01:07:37,000 --> 01:07:41,357
What beautiful performance. Beautiful.
Watch that mixture, watch that mixture.

787
01:07:41,560 --> 01:07:43,710
All right, all right.

788
01:07:44,760 --> 01:07:48,230
All right, that's my sweetie.
Good, climb, baby, climb.

789
01:07:48,400 --> 01:07:50,038
Come on, Earl.

790
01:07:50,200 --> 01:07:52,839
I can't concentrate. It's Vic's plane.

791
01:07:53,000 --> 01:07:57,437
That's it. Watch it.
Watch that mixture, take it easy.

792
01:08:01,240 --> 01:08:04,232
Good. He stopped.

793
01:08:09,360 --> 01:08:11,999
Earl. Earl, come quick!

794
01:08:13,600 --> 01:08:17,195
Where are you, are you
upstairs? Earl?

795
01:08:18,400 --> 01:08:21,949
-Vic, what happened?
-We're losing the house, babe.

796
01:08:26,840 --> 01:08:28,432
Vic's house is on fire.

797
01:08:28,600 --> 01:08:30,113
Did you call the fire department?

798
01:08:30,280 --> 01:08:33,750
My phone's dead.
Your phone's dead too.

799
01:08:36,600 --> 01:08:38,955
Water, water.

800
01:08:39,160 --> 01:08:43,711
Look. Look, there's no fire.
It's a trick.

801
01:08:45,840 --> 01:08:47,114
Oh, it was terrible.

802
01:08:47,320 --> 01:08:49,436
I had her up to 100 feet.
Everything was great.

803
01:08:49,600 --> 01:08:50,874
Then the controls jammed.

804
01:08:52,000 --> 01:08:53,353
I think it was that tower.

805
01:08:53,520 --> 01:08:56,637
-My signal couldn’t get to the servos.
-Poor baby.

806
01:08:56,840 --> 01:08:58,910
The motor cut out.
I knew it was in the soup.

807
01:08:59,080 --> 01:09:02,311
She went into a vertical spin,
hit the power lines, bounced up.

808
01:09:02,480 --> 01:09:04,630
And then she climbed 300 feet.

809
01:09:05,200 --> 01:09:08,431
You should’ve seen her.
She was magnificent.

810
01:09:08,600 --> 01:09:11,956
She just sort of stopped
and hung there.

811
01:09:12,120 --> 01:09:14,714
Then she nosed over and came
straight down into my attic.

812
01:09:14,880 --> 01:09:18,270
-The fuel pods exploded in seconds.
-Jesus.

813
01:09:18,520 --> 01:09:21,114
I stamped on the flames,
and everything spread so fast.

814
01:09:21,280 --> 01:09:22,872
That old house is Like a matchbox.

815
01:09:23,040 --> 01:09:26,271
If you hadn't had the keys to the car,
he could have driven to a phone.

816
01:09:26,440 --> 01:09:29,876
-What about his truck?
-You broke his rear axle, Daddy.

817
01:09:37,320 --> 01:09:39,151
All right, here, then. It works.

818
01:09:39,320 --> 01:09:41,629
Go ahead. Call the fire department.

819
01:09:41,800 --> 01:09:44,598
You see, he won't even use
the phone.

820
01:09:44,760 --> 01:09:46,990
This is just another one of
his cheap tricks.

821
01:09:47,160 --> 01:09:50,038
Isn't that right, Vic?

822
01:09:50,200 --> 01:09:51,633
Look at him, Enid.

823
01:09:51,800 --> 01:09:56,316
You're fawning all over a fake,
a phoney and a fraud.

824
01:10:03,960 --> 01:10:07,157
-Hey, brother, how about a beer?
-No, thank you.

825
01:10:08,800 --> 01:10:10,279
Look at that thing go.

826
01:10:10,440 --> 01:10:14,399
-What's wrong with the water?
-No pressure. Can't you see?

827
01:10:14,560 --> 01:10:17,836
-Well, what can we do about it?
-I know what we can do.

828
01:10:18,040 --> 01:10:19,917
-What?
-Get some marshmallows.

829
01:10:34,480 --> 01:10:37,677
Enid. Elaine.

830
01:10:38,680 --> 01:10:41,672
Relax. They're all gone.
They Left in your car.

831
01:10:41,880 --> 01:10:43,598
Elaine had a key.

832
01:10:43,760 --> 01:10:45,637
Vic made a trade.

833
01:10:45,800 --> 01:10:47,711
All of them for me.

834
01:10:49,920 --> 01:10:54,232
It's been less than 24 hours since
you and Vic moved in next door.

835
01:10:56,680 --> 01:10:59,797
-It seems Like years.
-A Lot has happened.

836
01:11:01,120 --> 01:11:03,111
You gonna miss Vic?

837
01:11:03,280 --> 01:11:04,679
Vic?

838
01:11:05,440 --> 01:11:07,158
I don't know.

839
01:11:07,680 --> 01:11:09,875
He was fantastic in bed.

840
01:11:10,040 --> 01:11:11,758
Until I got in it.

841
01:11:13,680 --> 01:11:16,319
You know, it's really great
that you can...

842
01:11:16,880 --> 01:11:20,793
...admit things Like that
in your relationship.

843
01:11:22,320 --> 01:11:24,231
You're really wonderful.

844
01:11:26,400 --> 01:11:29,119
That's what I've been trying to tell you.

845
01:11:33,000 --> 01:11:36,675
Is it so hard having your fantasies
come to Life?

846
01:11:38,920 --> 01:11:42,913
There's not a single living thing
Left on this road...

847
01:11:43,080 --> 01:11:45,310
<i>...except you and me.</i>

848
01:11:45,840 --> 01:11:49,958
You know what we're gonna do now,
Earl, just you and me?

849
01:11:51,720 --> 01:11:53,073
What?

850
01:11:53,240 --> 01:11:56,312
Have breakfast. Are you hungry?

851
01:11:57,080 --> 01:12:00,993
I'm starving, but there's no food
in the house.

852
01:12:01,160 --> 01:12:03,071
Well, if you have ketchup
and hot water...

853
01:12:03,240 --> 01:12:04,912
...I could make you tomato soup.

854
01:12:05,520 --> 01:12:06,839
Hey.

855
01:12:07,040 --> 01:12:10,237
I got a better idea. We'll go to the city.
We'll go anyplace you Like.

856
01:12:10,400 --> 01:12:12,550
What kind of food?
French, Spanish, fish?

857
01:12:13,440 --> 01:12:14,873
-I Like Greek.
-Greek. Great.

858
01:12:15,040 --> 01:12:16,792
I know a great Greek restaurant.

859
01:12:16,960 --> 01:12:19,110
-I'll go get a cab. I'll get ready-
-Oh, Earl?

860
01:12:19,480 --> 01:12:20,754
Yeah?

861
01:12:21,840 --> 01:12:25,628
I know just who I want for dessert.

862
01:13:46,440 --> 01:13:48,032
Ramona.

863
01:13:48,880 --> 01:13:50,711
Ramona?

864
01:13:56,600 --> 01:13:58,192
Ramona?

865
01:14:07,280 --> 01:14:09,077
Ramona.

866
01:14:10,880 --> 01:14:12,552
Surprise!

867
01:14:12,720 --> 01:14:14,233
See, buddy, I got you breakfast.

868
01:14:14,400 --> 01:14:16,789
Hey, Daddy, Vic brought
my five favorite junk foods.

869
01:14:16,960 --> 01:14:20,157
Elaine, get out the china. We'll inhale
this poison on the good stuff.

870
01:14:20,320 --> 01:14:23,915
-Where's all that plum sauce?
-It's in here, it's in here. Wait a second.

871
01:14:54,840 --> 01:14:57,115
Would you Like some wine, Enid?

872
01:15:01,880 --> 01:15:04,394
You know, I've been thinking, Enid.

873
01:15:05,280 --> 01:15:07,510
For the past couple of years...

874
01:15:07,680 --> 01:15:09,989
...things around here have been...

875
01:15:10,680 --> 01:15:11,954
...stagnant.

876
01:15:12,120 --> 01:15:15,715
Not uncomfortable, mind you, but...

877
01:15:15,880 --> 01:15:18,348
...changeless. Tedious.

878
01:15:19,520 --> 01:15:21,431
Except for Last night,
with Vic and Ramona.

879
01:15:21,720 --> 01:15:23,950
They're a sign. They're a revelation.

880
01:15:24,160 --> 01:15:27,550
They're squeezing the maximum yield
out of Life.

881
01:15:28,240 --> 01:15:30,470
Let's get back to the world
of the living.

882
01:15:30,640 --> 01:15:33,916
Let's move back to the city.
Or move to the country.

883
01:15:34,080 --> 01:15:36,275
I mean, this is neither.

884
01:15:37,400 --> 01:15:39,118
What do you say?

885
01:15:39,560 --> 01:15:41,915
I understand your restlessness, Earl.

886
01:15:42,080 --> 01:15:44,036
But true change comes only
from within.

887
01:15:44,200 --> 01:15:46,111
-Would you pass the wine?
-You feel it too?

888
01:15:46,280 --> 01:15:47,759
Not a bit.

889
01:15:47,920 --> 01:15:50,480
But I do think the city would be
a good idea.

890
01:15:50,640 --> 01:15:51,914
For you, in any case.

891
01:15:52,800 --> 01:15:54,711
But I meant for both of us.

892
01:15:54,920 --> 01:15:56,672
If we had the money...

893
01:15:57,040 --> 01:15:59,270
...I think I'd go back to school.

894
01:15:59,440 --> 01:16:01,158
I'd Like to...

895
01:16:01,320 --> 01:16:05,154
...intensify my Native American
art studies.

896
01:16:05,320 --> 01:16:07,595
We'll have the money.
We'll sell the house.

897
01:16:07,760 --> 01:16:10,228
Vic, here, will buy it.
He's rolling in dough.

898
01:16:10,400 --> 01:16:13,836
Why do you think he crashed his plane
into his house and burned it down?

899
01:16:14,040 --> 01:16:15,393
Why, Daddy?

900
01:16:15,600 --> 01:16:17,909
For the insurance money. Right, Vic?

901
01:16:18,080 --> 01:16:20,514
How much you have the old place
insured for?

902
01:16:21,720 --> 01:16:23,756
He didn't have any insurance.

903
01:16:23,920 --> 01:16:25,512
He never does.

904
01:16:25,920 --> 01:16:27,239
Of course he had insurance.

905
01:16:27,400 --> 01:16:30,551
The bank wouldn’t give him a mortgage
without insurance.

906
01:16:32,440 --> 01:16:34,715
He didn't have a mortgage.

907
01:16:36,480 --> 01:16:38,277
You paid cash?

908
01:16:39,040 --> 01:16:40,917
You rented?

909
01:16:41,440 --> 01:16:43,749
Do you remember
when your neighbor, Mrs. Warren...

910
01:16:43,960 --> 01:16:46,758
...moved to Riverside Nursing Home
after her husband died?

911
01:16:46,920 --> 01:16:49,195
Well, that's when we met her.

912
01:16:50,080 --> 01:16:51,798
Vic used to dress her all the time.

913
01:16:52,880 --> 01:16:55,678
Mrs. Warren would always
ask for Vic.

914
01:16:56,880 --> 01:16:58,632
Well, when she died...

915
01:16:58,800 --> 01:17:00,711
...the house was empty,
so we moved in.

916
01:17:02,440 --> 01:17:04,556
Vic said she wouldn’t mind.

917
01:17:06,120 --> 01:17:08,236
I said it was a steal.

918
01:17:10,560 --> 01:17:12,676
This is really something.

919
01:17:13,120 --> 01:17:15,793
<i>You two ought to be on 60 Minutes.</i>

920
01:17:17,960 --> 01:17:20,952
Yeah, but now we don't have
no place to live.

921
01:17:22,640 --> 01:17:24,232
Daddy, they could live in my room.

922
01:17:24,400 --> 01:17:26,755
Dick's invited me to Florida
for a couple of weeks.

923
01:17:26,920 --> 01:17:28,956
His mom won't be there.
She said it's okay.

924
01:17:29,120 --> 01:17:32,351
You stay out of this. You're not going
anywhere and Dick is off-limits.

925
01:17:32,680 --> 01:17:35,433
Maybe that's not a bad idea
that Elaine had.

926
01:17:35,600 --> 01:17:37,511
I mean, they could stay
in the guest room.

927
01:17:37,680 --> 01:17:40,797
I don't know. That room's loaded
with a Lot of furniture and junk.

928
01:17:40,960 --> 01:17:43,838
If we did stay, we'd really need
the big room, facing the road.

929
01:17:44,160 --> 01:17:45,832
The master bedroom?

930
01:17:46,040 --> 01:17:48,270
Hey, don't worry, we'd earn our keep
around here.

931
01:17:48,480 --> 01:17:49,754
How wonderful.

932
01:17:49,920 --> 01:17:51,672
-No heavy yard work, though.
-Hernia.

933
01:17:51,840 --> 01:17:53,956
Well, I don't know, it is my bedroom.

934
01:17:54,120 --> 01:17:57,032
I kind of have a sentimental
attachment to it.

935
01:17:57,200 --> 01:17:58,474
I'll tell you what.

936
01:17:58,640 --> 01:18:00,392
With a scrub-down
and some carpentry...

937
01:18:00,560 --> 01:18:02,869
...we could make conditions liveable
in the garage.

938
01:18:03,040 --> 01:18:04,268
Garage, huh?

939
01:18:04,880 --> 01:18:08,395
Right. That's it, then.
Ramona, let's hit the road.

940
01:18:08,600 --> 01:18:11,512
Please. Look, I was just kidding.

941
01:18:11,720 --> 01:18:14,632
I want you to stay. Both of you.
You're worth it.

942
01:18:15,120 --> 01:18:16,792
Please stay.

943
01:18:16,960 --> 01:18:18,359
As my friends.

944
01:18:23,480 --> 01:18:24,708
Please.

945
01:18:24,880 --> 01:18:27,269
Stay here, in the outer limits
of the dead-end zone?

946
01:18:27,680 --> 01:18:30,240
Nothing personal, but Life
at the end of the road...

947
01:18:30,440 --> 01:18:33,750
...just ain't for Captain Vic
and Empress Ramona.

948
01:18:33,920 --> 01:18:38,118
Sorry, folks, but you can
color us gone.

949
01:18:41,200 --> 01:18:44,272
Boy, they were neat.

950
01:18:45,320 --> 01:18:47,390
They were beyond neat.

951
01:18:48,200 --> 01:18:50,350
They were extraordinary...

952
01:18:50,520 --> 01:18:52,272
<i>...unique...</i>

953
01:18:53,000 --> 01:18:54,911
...special.

954
01:18:55,080 --> 01:18:56,752
Earl, can you write me a check?

955
01:18:56,920 --> 01:18:59,673
I'm gonna need some money
this week.

956
01:19:00,560 --> 01:19:03,120
-How much?
-How much is in the account?

957
01:19:03,280 --> 01:19:04,554
I don't know.

958
01:19:04,720 --> 01:19:06,631
Where's the checkbook?

959
01:19:08,120 --> 01:19:09,712
The checkbook!

960
01:19:11,080 --> 01:19:13,230
-I'm hungry again. You wanna eat?
-Oh, yeah.

961
01:19:13,400 --> 01:19:17,279
Hold it. Hold it right there, folks.

962
01:19:20,320 --> 01:19:22,197
All right.

963
01:19:22,600 --> 01:19:24,192
Let me have it.

964
01:19:24,360 --> 01:19:26,157
What are you talking about
now, Earl?

965
01:19:26,320 --> 01:19:29,915
My checkbook. Not that there's
any money Left in my account.

966
01:19:30,080 --> 01:19:31,479
That's what you think of me?

967
01:19:31,640 --> 01:19:34,200
I take your hospitality,
I break bread with your family.

968
01:19:34,360 --> 01:19:35,793
You still think I'd rob you?

969
01:19:35,960 --> 01:19:37,552
Look, just give me the checkbook.

970
01:19:37,720 --> 01:19:41,599
I'm not even gonna talk about
the $32 you stole from me Last night...

971
01:19:41,760 --> 01:19:43,671
...when you were
supposed to get dinner...

972
01:19:43,840 --> 01:19:46,149
...and cooked that bogus
spaghetti meal instead.

973
01:19:46,320 --> 01:19:47,594
Your checkbook.

974
01:19:47,760 --> 01:19:50,069
It's on the table in the hall,
next to your wallet.

975
01:19:50,240 --> 01:19:53,516
My wallet! Enid?
Look on the table in the hall.

976
01:19:53,720 --> 01:19:55,995
Do you see my wallet
and checkbook there?

977
01:19:56,840 --> 01:19:59,229
Elaine, get ready to call the police.

978
01:19:59,400 --> 01:20:01,231
Oh, Earl.

979
01:20:01,400 --> 01:20:03,356
Hey. Kojak.

980
01:20:03,560 --> 01:20:05,516
How much is Left in the account?

981
01:20:06,400 --> 01:20:10,598
There's $310 Left in the account.

982
01:20:10,760 --> 01:20:14,548
Vic spent $17 on pants and a shirt
from Goodwill.

983
01:20:14,720 --> 01:20:19,271
And there's a receipt here for $32...

984
01:20:19,440 --> 01:20:21,351
...from Mr. Fong's Fast Chow.

985
01:20:21,520 --> 01:20:24,830
Do you want me to call
the National Guard now, Daddy?

986
01:20:25,000 --> 01:20:26,558
-Elaine, get the car.
-What for?

987
01:20:26,720 --> 01:20:29,029
Just do as I ask.

988
01:20:29,200 --> 01:20:30,918
Please.

989
01:20:31,080 --> 01:20:32,718
Give me the wallet.

990
01:20:33,880 --> 01:20:35,711
All right, now...

991
01:20:35,880 --> 01:20:38,394
...I don't want any argument
about this.

992
01:20:38,960 --> 01:20:43,112
This is the Least I can do after all
the trouble I've put you two through.

993
01:20:43,280 --> 01:20:46,431
I just hope that someday
you can forgive me.

994
01:20:46,600 --> 01:20:48,238
-Here.
-What's that?

995
01:20:48,400 --> 01:20:49,958
It's his vehicle registration.

996
01:20:50,120 --> 01:20:52,475
He just signed over his car to us.

997
01:20:52,640 --> 01:20:53,914
Really, Earl?

998
01:20:54,080 --> 01:20:56,389
Yes. It's all yours.

999
01:20:56,560 --> 01:20:59,950
I- I want you to have it...

1000
01:21:00,120 --> 01:21:02,680
<i>...because, well...</i>

1001
01:21:02,840 --> 01:21:04,956
Because I just want you to have it...

1002
01:21:05,120 --> 01:21:07,714
...and to get safely to wherever
you're going.

1003
01:21:07,880 --> 01:21:11,839
And, maybe, time and again, you might
think about your old neighbors...

1004
01:21:12,000 --> 01:21:13,274
...here on Burt Street.

1005
01:21:13,440 --> 01:21:15,476
What's happening, Daddy?

1006
01:21:16,160 --> 01:21:19,232
Your old man just gave me
his car, honey.

1007
01:21:19,400 --> 01:21:22,312
-I don't know what to say.
-Oh, you don't have to say anything.

1008
01:21:22,480 --> 01:21:23,959
It doesn't seem enough.

1009
01:21:24,120 --> 01:21:25,678
Oh, Earl.

1010
01:21:25,840 --> 01:21:29,389
You are the best.

1011
01:21:29,560 --> 01:21:32,870
Hey, come on. Take it easy,
super stud.

1012
01:21:33,040 --> 01:21:35,110
You make me Look bad.

1013
01:21:40,120 --> 01:21:43,715
So make sure you take care
of my Little Burt Street beauties.

1014
01:21:43,880 --> 01:21:45,916
-I'll try.
-All right.

1015
01:21:49,160 --> 01:21:50,718
Some time we had, huh?

1016
01:21:50,880 --> 01:21:53,348
Don't drive too long.
You haven't had much sleep.

1017
01:21:53,520 --> 01:21:55,670
Remember those shots
I took at you Last night?

1018
01:21:55,880 --> 01:21:57,154
Yeah, I remember.

1019
01:21:57,360 --> 01:21:58,713
Come here.

1020
01:22:00,080 --> 01:22:03,117
I knew it was you.
That's why I missed.

1021
01:22:03,960 --> 01:22:05,279
Thanks, Vic.

1022
01:22:05,440 --> 01:22:08,113
Oh, I almost forgot.
Check the sticker on the door panel.

1023
01:22:08,280 --> 01:22:10,669
She'll need an oil change
in about 1000 miles.

1024
01:22:10,840 --> 01:22:13,593
Use Wolf’s Head Golden 30-weight.

1025
01:22:13,760 --> 01:22:15,079
It'll never Let you down.

1026
01:22:15,440 --> 01:22:17,237
Thanks, buddy.

1027
01:22:20,520 --> 01:22:22,238
Okay, pal.

1028
01:22:22,400 --> 01:22:25,233
-Bye, folks.
-Goodbye.

1029
01:22:25,400 --> 01:22:27,834
Oh, we'll miss you.
I wish you weren't going.

1030
01:22:28,000 --> 01:22:30,116
-Don't forget to write, huh?
-Bye.

1031
01:22:30,280 --> 01:22:32,430
Be cool, guys.

1032
01:22:50,200 --> 01:22:52,668
<i>And now back to
our afternoon feature...</i>

1033
01:22:52,840 --> 01:22:56,355
<i>...Redstone Romance, starring
Clive Breck er...</i>

1034
01:22:56,520 --> 01:22:59,159
<i>...Marjorie Crane and Sky Saxon.</i>

1035
01:22:59,320 --> 01:23:02,790
Hey, Dad, thanks.
It was far-out. Goodbye.

1036
01:23:02,960 --> 01:23:04,598
-Where you going?
-Back to school.

1037
01:23:05,600 --> 01:23:07,636
Back to school?
I thought you got kicked out.

1038
01:23:07,840 --> 01:23:11,753
Connie Schiff confessed.
They threw her out and cleared me.

1039
01:23:11,920 --> 01:23:15,629
Oh, that's my ride. I gotta go
or I'll miss the train. Bye, Dad.

1040
01:23:21,240 --> 01:23:23,959
-Elaine, I don't want you in that truck!
-I can't hear you.

1041
01:23:24,120 --> 01:23:28,352
I'll call you next week. Don't forget
to mall my allowance. Bye.

1042
01:23:28,520 --> 01:23:30,829
See you later, wart-head.

1043
01:23:36,560 --> 01:23:38,755
Bye, Daddy.

1044
01:23:48,320 --> 01:23:49,594
Where are you going?

1045
01:23:49,760 --> 01:23:53,355
Oh, I have an emergency meeting of my
Native American art study circle.

1046
01:23:53,520 --> 01:23:56,512
-Where'd that getup come from?
-It was a present.

1047
01:23:56,680 --> 01:23:58,159
Oh, that must be Mr. Thundersky.

1048
01:23:58,320 --> 01:24:01,278
-Mr. Thundersky?
-My ride.

1049
01:24:01,440 --> 01:24:05,399
-Who the hell is that?
-Don't wait up. Bye.

1050
01:24:50,200 --> 01:24:54,751
<i>Hello. I'm Charles Haults, president
of Spruce Hill Memorial Chapels.</i>

1051
01:24:54,920 --> 01:24:58,629
<i>For over 50 years, West Valley
families have trusted Spruce Hill...</i>

1052
01:24:58,800 --> 01:25:01,917
<i>...with the interment and care
of their loved ones.</i>

1053
01:25:02,080 --> 01:25:05,072
<i>Now, Spruce Hill Park
and Spruce Hill Monuments...</i>

1054
01:25:05,240 --> 01:25:09,677
<i>...join to offer you a modern concept
in funeral aftercare.</i>

1055
01:25:09,840 --> 01:25:12,274
<i>For the entombment
you've always dreamed of...</i>

1056
01:25:12,440 --> 01:25:14,556
<i>...Spruce Hill now introduces
an exclusive...</i>

1057
01:25:14,720 --> 01:25:17,757
<i>...aboveground display chamber.</i>

1058
01:25:18,280 --> 01:25:21,477
<i>Spruce Hill's aboveground
entombment utilizes a method called...</i>

1059
01:25:21,640 --> 01:25:23,870
<i>...uniform Plexiglas enclosure.</i>

1060
01:25:24,040 --> 01:25:26,076
<i>It ensures permanent preservation...</i>

1061
01:25:26,240 --> 01:25:29,437
<i>...so your loved ones will be able
to see clearly and vividly...</i>

1062
01:25:29,600 --> 01:25:32,273
<i>...the object of their grief, forever.</i>

1063
01:25:32,440 --> 01:25:35,000
<i>Visit Spruce Hill's
Aboveground display chamber.</i>

1064
01:25:35,160 --> 01:25:38,948
<i>The time to choose your case is now.</i>

1065
01:25:43,840 --> 01:25:45,478
Ramona!

1066
01:25:45,640 --> 01:25:47,631
I see you still have
the same old wallpaper.

1067
01:25:47,800 --> 01:25:49,074
Hey.

1068
01:25:49,280 --> 01:25:51,236
You two make a sharp couple.

1069
01:25:52,000 --> 01:25:54,434
You wouldn’t believe it.
It happened at the same time.

1070
01:25:54,600 --> 01:25:57,876
Vic stared at me. I stared at him.
We both knew it was wrong.

1071
01:25:58,040 --> 01:26:00,076
It's just not gonna be any fun
without you.

1072
01:26:00,240 --> 01:26:02,515
Honest? Does that mean you’ll stay?

1073
01:26:02,680 --> 01:26:05,069
-We've got plenty of room.
-No, no. We're past that.

1074
01:26:05,240 --> 01:26:07,959
-You're coming with us.
-Really?

1075
01:26:08,120 --> 01:26:10,554
Me come with you?
No, you don't mean it.

1076
01:26:10,720 --> 01:26:12,517
Sure we mean it. It'll be a blast.

1077
01:26:12,680 --> 01:26:15,240
Come on, Let’s go. We're getting old.

1078
01:26:16,200 --> 01:26:18,873
-The dishwasher's on.
-It'll stay on.

1079
01:26:23,960 --> 01:26:27,270
All right, damn it. You're on.
Let's do it.

1080
01:26:27,440 --> 01:26:30,512
This is crazy, but there's something
so right about it. Let's go.

1081
01:26:30,680 --> 01:26:34,753
-Hold it. Not so fast, pal.
-What?

1082
01:26:34,920 --> 01:26:38,629
Don't you think you should
Leave a note for Enid?

1083
01:26:38,800 --> 01:26:44,318
You're right. In fact, I'll Leave
a Little more than just a note.

1084
01:27:57,760 --> 01:28:02,151
No, no, no. Up front,
right next to Captain Vic.

1085
01:28:02,320 --> 01:28:04,117
-Where are we going?
-How should I know?

1086
01:28:04,280 --> 01:28:06,794
You tell me. I'm just driving.

1087
01:28:17,520 --> 01:28:20,432
-Off into the land of the great unknown.
-Look.

1088
01:28:20,960 --> 01:28:24,430
You weren't kidding. You really are
Leaving a Little more than a note.

1089
01:28:24,600 --> 01:28:27,797
Well, Enid never did Like to come home
to a dark house.

1090
